abstract: Court of Arbitration for Sport rules that level of natural testosterone in athlete's body does not suffice to bar some women from competing against other women in professional sports, in case involving Indian sprinter Dutee Chand; ruling ends practice of so-called hyperandrogenism by International Assn of Athletics Federations, governing body of track and field, and reaffirms trend in which gender is viewed as part of spectrum.
lead_paragraph: An arbitration panel in Switzerland ruled that it was not necessary for I.A.A.F., track and field’s governing body, to exclude female athletes with high testosterone levels.

headline.main: Dutee Chand, Female Sprinter With High Testosterone Level, Wins Right to Compete
headline.print_headline: A Win for Athletes Whose Sex Was Questioned
